Beaver dam and beaver lodge on Hat Lake.  Click on photo, which will then give you the option to go to my Flickr site to get a better view.

The beavers came out and foraged every evening during our visit there in July 2005.  By the following summer and after (2006-2016), they were gone, supposedly dying from disease, according to the park staff.  The lake dynamics have changed ever since the dam started to break down in 2007.  By 2011, the dam had completely disappeared, and the lodge was on high ground.  Hat Lake is now Hat Creek!

description:
Dark phase adult observed in concrete lined brow ditch, then fled upslope. Surprising find in Rice Canyon. The Paseo Del Rey development around Rice Canyon started somewhere around late 1993/early 1994, and the finger canyons in that area have become virtually isolated. Large volume roads and freeways further cleaved what little connectivity was left. 

I'm wondering if this could have been captured further south, kept as a pet, then released in the canyon. It's not too far out of range, but I don't know of any records from that area of Chula Vista.

Here's a description of the snake:

"Large Coluber sp. with no lateral stripes (opposed to smaller C. lateralis), out of range for C.flagellum.

Dark phase (virtually patternless brownish-black), white blotches by eyes and lower jaw, with faint white vertical marking on the sides of the neck."
